16
00:00:53,187 --> 00:00:56,789
fishermen like to exaggerate  
about the size of their catches.

17
00:00:56,791 --> 00:00:58,724
in 19th century japan,     

18
00:00:58,726 --> 00:01:02,261
fish rubbings were used for actual documentation.   

19
00:01:02,263 --> 00:01:05,331
fishermen coated the fish with non-toxic ink       

20
00:01:05,333 --> 00:01:07,933
and rubbed it on paper to transfer the image.     

21
00:01:07,935 --> 00:01:11,237
they called this form of record-keeping gyotaku.   

22
00:01:12,407 --> 00:01:14,273
♪          

23
00:01:14,275 --> 00:01:16,609
over time, the practice of fish rubbings        

24
00:01:16,611 --> 00:01:19,277
has evolved into an art form. 

25
00:01:19,279 --> 00:01:24,550
why paint a picture when you can
print one using the real thing?

26
00:01:24,552 --> 00:01:29,555
the artist traces the outline of the fish onto a foam block. 

27
00:01:29,557 --> 00:01:34,359
following that outline, he cuts
out a fish-shaped cavity.   

28
00:01:34,361 --> 00:01:36,295
he sets the fish in the cavity.

29
00:01:36,297 --> 00:01:37,963
the foam will keep the fish level         

30
00:01:37,965 --> 00:01:41,634
and stable during printing.  

31
00:01:41,636 --> 00:01:43,903
he tucks paper wadding into the mouth         

32
00:01:43,905 --> 00:01:46,772
to keep it open for a more interesting print.   

33
00:01:46,774 --> 00:01:48,774
♪          

34
00:01:48,776 --> 00:01:51,309
he also inserts wadding under the gill flaps      

35
00:01:51,311 --> 00:01:55,648
to impede the flow of fluids from the fish.    

36
00:01:55,650 --> 00:01:57,983
he props up the fins with pins 

37
00:01:57,985 --> 00:02:02,321
and leaves them to dry overnight
in this elevated position.   

38
00:02:02,323 --> 00:02:06,792
this will give the rubbed image
the illusion of action.    

39
00:02:06,794 --> 00:02:09,729
he wraps cosmetic sponges around wine corks       

40
00:02:09,731 --> 00:02:11,998
and tapes them at the base.  

41
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:13,999
these improvised ink applicators

42
00:02:14,001 --> 00:02:18,070
will eventually provide a smooth
finish with no brush strokes. 

43
00:02:18,072 --> 00:02:22,742
he makes one for each color, plus a few extra for blending. 

44
00:02:22,744 --> 00:02:24,676
next, he selects different ink colors      

45
00:02:24,678 --> 00:02:27,213
to create a bluish green shade 

46
00:02:27,215 --> 00:02:30,148
that's close to the one on the bluegill.        

47
00:02:30,150 --> 00:02:33,219
he adds poppyseed oil to thin the inks a bit     

48
00:02:33,221 --> 00:02:35,354
and blends it all with a palette knife.     

49
00:02:35,356 --> 00:02:37,623
♪          

50
00:02:37,625 --> 00:02:42,160
with the fins now dry and stiff,
he removes the pins.      

51
00:02:42,162 --> 00:02:44,363
with a metal probe, he pulls up a fin       

52
00:02:44,365 --> 00:02:47,633
that hadn't been raised earlier.

53
00:02:47,635 --> 00:02:50,770
he places a paper towel between the foam support block 

54
00:02:50,772 --> 00:02:53,238
and the fish.         

55
00:02:53,240 --> 00:02:55,774
♪          

56
00:02:55,776 --> 00:02:58,244
he pats a greenish black color onto the gills   

57
00:02:58,246 --> 00:03:00,913
and tail using a foam brush.  

58
00:03:00,915 --> 00:03:04,050
this process leaves some smears
on the paper towel,      

59
00:03:04,052 --> 00:03:06,652
but that's what it's there for.

60
00:03:06,654 --> 00:03:09,354
switching to one of the improvised applicators,  

61
00:03:09,356 --> 00:03:11,523
he applies the bluish green ink

62
00:03:11,525 --> 00:03:15,461
to the upper part of the fish's body.      

63
00:03:15,463 --> 00:03:18,798
he dabs a yellow color onto the belly of the fish.  

64
00:03:18,800 --> 00:03:21,867
♪          

65
00:03:21,869 --> 00:03:23,802
he adds a bit of red to the chest          

66
00:03:23,804 --> 00:03:25,670
because during spawning,    

67
00:03:25,672 --> 00:03:27,672
it usually turns this color.  

68
00:03:27,674 --> 00:03:29,742
♪          

69
00:03:29,744 --> 00:03:31,943
he places a piece of paper under a fin          

70
00:03:31,945 --> 00:03:35,548
as he coats it with green ink. 

71
00:03:35,550 --> 00:03:37,682
then he removes the paper towel

72
00:03:37,684 --> 00:03:40,486
that has protected the foam support block from smudges   

73
00:03:40,488 --> 00:03:44,890
and places the fish back in the cavity.      

74
00:03:44,892 --> 00:03:48,427
he lightly sprays a sheet of rice paper with water.   

75
00:03:48,429 --> 00:03:50,362
this makes it easier to manipulate,         

76
00:03:50,364 --> 00:03:53,899
as he drapes the damp paper onto the inked fish.      

77
00:03:53,901 --> 00:03:56,702
♪          

78
00:03:56,704 --> 00:04:01,373
he rubs the paper onto the inked
fish to transfer the image.  

79
00:04:01,375 --> 00:04:05,578
this takes skill and the right touch.      

80
00:04:05,580 --> 00:04:06,979
once he's finished,      

81
00:04:06,981 --> 00:04:09,381
the artist peels the paper away from the fish  

82
00:04:09,383 --> 00:04:12,651
and examines the rubbing.   

83
00:04:12,653 --> 00:04:14,386
after the ink has dried,    

84
00:04:14,388 --> 00:04:16,422
he lightly sprays the rubbing with water     

85
00:04:16,424 --> 00:04:18,657
and then a water-based dye.  

86
00:04:18,659 --> 00:04:20,926
the dye provides background color        

87
00:04:20,928 --> 00:04:23,862
but doesn't affect the oil-based ink guard.    

88
00:04:23,864 --> 00:04:26,665
♪          

89
00:04:26,667 --> 00:04:30,536
he brushes wheat paste onto a second piece of rice paper. 

90
00:04:30,538 --> 00:04:33,539
this paper will serve as an extra layer of reinforcement

91
00:04:33,541 --> 00:04:35,007
for the fish rubbing.     

92
00:04:35,009 --> 00:04:38,610
♪          

93
00:04:38,612 --> 00:04:42,547
he wets the rubbing thoroughly.

94
00:04:42,549 --> 00:04:46,352
an assistant slowly lowers the wet print onto the paper  

95
00:04:46,354 --> 00:04:48,888
as the artist smoothes the rubbing,     

96
00:04:48,890 --> 00:04:53,559
ensuring there are no wrinkles as it adheres.   

97
00:04:53,561 --> 00:04:56,896
the image of the fish's eye  
doesn't transfer during rubbing,

98
00:04:56,898 --> 00:04:58,631
so he paints one.       

99
00:04:58,633 --> 00:05:01,499
he defines the pupil with black watercolor     

100
00:05:01,501 --> 00:05:03,902
and paints the iris yellow.  

101
00:05:03,904 --> 00:05:08,774
the painted eye adds a soulful expression to the print.    

102
00:05:08,776 --> 00:05:11,043
the fish rubbing is now ready to be mounted    

103
00:05:11,045 --> 00:05:15,648
to a more rigid paper backing for extra support.       

104
00:05:15,650 --> 00:05:19,051
he trims the borders, ensuring that they're symmetrical    

105
00:05:19,053 --> 00:05:20,653
and the correct measurements. 

106
00:05:20,655 --> 00:05:22,788
♪          

107
00:05:22,790 --> 00:05:25,457
he then tapes the fish rubbing to the mounting board     

108
00:05:25,459 --> 00:05:27,593
and signs it.         

109
00:05:27,595 --> 00:05:31,263
with numerous and extensive dryings between steps,     

110
00:05:31,265 --> 00:05:34,767
it has taken several weeks to produce this fish rubbing. 

111
00:05:44,145 --> 00:05:48,547
♪          

112
00:05:48,549 --> 00:05:52,150
narrator: clay shooting machines
launch the flying targets   

113
00:05:52,152 --> 00:05:54,753
used in the sport of clay pigeon shooting.     

114
00:05:54,755 --> 00:05:57,689
the saucer-shaped targets are called clay pigeons    

115
00:05:57,691 --> 00:06:02,027
because they replace the original targets, live pigeons.

116
00:06:02,029 --> 00:06:04,162
shooting machines can launch the targets     

117
00:06:04,164 --> 00:06:08,434
at various intervals, angles and velocities.     

118
00:06:08,436 --> 00:06:09,902
♪          

119
00:06:09,904 --> 00:06:11,103
this company has been building 

120
00:06:11,105 --> 00:06:14,707
clay shooting machines since 1927.          

121
00:06:14,709 --> 00:06:17,710
older models like this one were heavy steel clunkers 

122
00:06:17,712 --> 00:06:19,511
that ran on high voltage,   

123
00:06:19,513 --> 00:06:24,516
were difficult to move around and weren't terribly precise. 

124
00:06:24,518 --> 00:06:28,587
today's machines weigh from just 88 to 220 pounds.  

125
00:06:28,589 --> 00:06:30,856
not only are they easily portable,     

126
00:06:30,858 --> 00:06:32,725
they run on just 12 volts   

127
00:06:32,727 --> 00:06:36,394
and perform with great precision.     

128
00:06:36,396 --> 00:06:41,266
the machine's sturdy base   
is constructed from thick steel.

129
00:06:41,268 --> 00:06:44,336
its parts were cut by a computer-guided laser   

130
00:06:44,338 --> 00:06:46,605
then welded together.     

131
00:06:46,607 --> 00:06:49,541
♪          

132
00:06:49,543 --> 00:06:51,543
the base design enables the machine      

133
00:06:51,545 --> 00:06:55,414
to move both laterally and vertically.        

134
00:06:55,416 --> 00:06:58,083
the first component the worker attaches to the base  

135
00:06:58,085 --> 00:06:59,484
is the frame.         

136
00:06:59,486 --> 00:07:02,421
made of durable epoxy-coated cast aluminum,         

137
00:07:02,423 --> 00:07:06,358
it supports all the machine's key components. 

138
00:07:06,360 --> 00:07:09,428
one of them, the main shaft assembly for the throwing arm, 

139
00:07:09,430 --> 00:07:11,096
is already installed.     

140
00:07:11,098 --> 00:07:14,500
♪          

141
00:07:14,502 --> 00:07:16,701
a technician connects the frame to the base     

142
00:07:16,703 --> 00:07:18,304
with heavy-duty bolts.     

143
00:07:18,306 --> 00:07:22,240
♪          

144
00:07:22,242 --> 00:07:26,311
this slot in the frame allows the machine to tilt vertically,

145
00:07:26,313 --> 00:07:28,380
up to 65 degrees.       

146
00:07:28,382 --> 00:07:31,383
♪          

147
00:07:31,385 --> 00:07:34,520
he attaches a steel extension for the throwing plate     

148
00:07:34,522 --> 00:07:38,390
across which the throwing arm moves the clay pigeon.     

149
00:07:38,392 --> 00:07:40,191
this extension enables an optimal       

150
00:07:40,193 --> 00:07:43,395
positioning of the throwing plate.     

151
00:07:43,397 --> 00:07:45,330
before installing the throwing plate,      

152
00:07:45,332 --> 00:07:48,667
he installs the indexing shaft assembly.        

153
00:07:48,669 --> 00:07:50,469
the indexing shaft is the finger

154
00:07:50,471 --> 00:07:52,604
that moves the carousel forward

155
00:07:52,606 --> 00:07:55,340
one column at a time.     

156
00:07:55,342 --> 00:07:57,876
he mounts the steel throwing plate.        

157
00:07:57,878 --> 00:08:01,146
it has three steel springs on its underside.       

158
00:08:01,148 --> 00:08:02,480
one goes over the bolt,    

159
00:08:02,482 --> 00:08:05,683
attaching it to the far end of the extension.       

160
00:08:05,685 --> 00:08:09,488
the other two go over the bolt,
attaching it to the frame.   

161
00:08:09,490 --> 00:08:12,758
these springs keep the arm parallel to the throwing plate.

162
00:08:12,760 --> 00:08:15,360
♪          

163
00:08:15,362 --> 00:08:19,498
next, he screws the throwing arm
to the main shaft assembly.  

164
00:08:19,500 --> 00:08:26,171
♪          

165
00:08:26,173 --> 00:08:29,241
he checks the gap between the arm and plate   

166
00:08:29,243 --> 00:08:32,378
to make sure the arm makes contact with the clay pigeon  

167
00:08:32,380 --> 00:08:34,880
at just the right level.    

168
00:08:37,518 --> 00:08:41,086
if the alignment's off, he   
adjusts the height of the plate.

169
00:08:41,088 --> 00:08:45,224
♪          

170
00:08:45,226 --> 00:08:47,926
then he manually turns the main shaft         

171
00:08:47,928 --> 00:08:50,796
to make sure the throwing arm rotates smoothly.       

172
00:08:53,333 --> 00:08:56,134
the machine runs on a powerful electric motor   

173
00:08:56,136 --> 00:08:58,470
that has an integrated gear train.          

174
00:08:58,472 --> 00:09:05,344
♪          

175
00:09:05,346 --> 00:09:08,080
the technician installs the motor on the frame     

176
00:09:08,082 --> 00:09:11,550
beneath the main shaft assembly.

177
00:09:11,552 --> 00:09:14,553
next, he attaches the steel arming spring    

178
00:09:14,555 --> 00:09:18,824
which can withstand up to 440 pounds of pull force.  

179
00:09:18,826 --> 00:09:21,560
its sudden release generates the propulsion    

180
00:09:21,562 --> 00:09:22,961
to launch the clay pigeon   

181
00:09:22,963 --> 00:09:26,331
of a flying speed of more than 62 miles per hour.    

182
00:09:28,568 --> 00:09:30,902
he mounts the support base for the carousel        

183
00:09:30,904 --> 00:09:32,838
that holds the clay pigeons,  

184
00:09:32,840 --> 00:09:36,775
then he screws the arming spring
to the main shaft assembly.  

185
00:09:36,777 --> 00:09:39,111
as the shaft swings back and forth,        

186
00:09:39,113 --> 00:09:42,414
it stretches and releases the spring.      

187
00:09:42,416 --> 00:09:44,650
he links the indexing shaft assembly  

188
00:09:44,652 --> 00:09:46,351
to the motor's gear shaft.   

189
00:09:49,456 --> 00:09:52,257
he installs the carousel, made of cast aluminum,     

190
00:09:52,259 --> 00:09:54,259
on the support base.      

191
00:09:54,261 --> 00:09:58,329
♪          

192
00:09:58,331 --> 00:10:00,866
this model has a different type of motor design      

193
00:10:00,868 --> 00:10:03,468
that enables the base to pivot automatically,    

194
00:10:03,470 --> 00:10:07,406
launching random trajectories. 

195
00:10:07,408 --> 00:10:11,809
this patented system increases the carousel's capacity.    

196
00:10:11,811 --> 00:10:13,811
by clicking retractable extensions           

197
00:10:13,813 --> 00:10:16,348
onto the rods that separate the columns,   

198
00:10:16,350 --> 00:10:18,283
the operator can stack 50 percent      

199
00:10:18,285 --> 00:10:21,220
more clay pigeons in the carousel.        

200
00:10:21,222 --> 00:10:23,889
when the operator presses a button on the remote control,

201
00:10:23,891 --> 00:10:26,424
the throwing arm rotation begins.        

202
00:10:26,426 --> 00:10:29,094
when the arm passes a specific point,       

203
00:10:29,096 --> 00:10:33,164
the stretched arming spring releases, launching the pigeon.

204
00:10:33,166 --> 00:10:35,567
as the arm continues its rotation,         

205
00:10:35,569 --> 00:10:39,037
the linked indexing shaft moves the carousel forward,  

206
00:10:39,039 --> 00:10:42,307
dropping a new clay pigeon onto the throwing plate.    

207
00:10:42,309 --> 00:10:46,512
when the arm comes full circle,
re-stretching the arming spring,

208
00:10:46,514 --> 00:10:48,647
a sensor cuts power to the motor

209
00:10:48,649 --> 00:10:50,982
until the next press of the button.         

210
00:10:50,984 --> 00:10:54,486
this entire cycle takes just 2 seconds.     

211
00:11:01,862 --> 00:11:06,265
♪          

212
00:11:06,267 --> 00:11:10,068
narrator: almond consumption dates back to biblical times. 

213
00:11:10,070 --> 00:11:12,538
they're even mentioned in the old testament.     

214
00:11:12,540 --> 00:11:14,272
around 100 a.d.,        

215
00:11:14,274 --> 00:11:17,209
the ancient romans showered newlyweds with almonds.    

216
00:11:17,211 --> 00:11:20,678
this ritual came from the belief
that they increased fertility. 

217
00:11:20,680 --> 00:11:23,415
but today, it's the nutritional
value of almonds        

218
00:11:23,417 --> 00:11:26,084
that keeps us coming back for more.     

219
00:11:26,086 --> 00:11:29,087
♪          

220
00:11:29,089 --> 00:11:31,756
almonds are a guilt-free snack.

221
00:11:31,758 --> 00:11:36,494
they're full of vitamins, minerals and protein.     

222
00:11:36,496 --> 00:11:38,096
more than 80 percent of the world's         

223
00:11:38,098 --> 00:11:40,031
almonds come from california  

224
00:11:40,033 --> 00:11:43,034
where growing conditions are ideal.           

225
00:11:43,036 --> 00:11:45,704
upon arrival at a processing facility,     

226
00:11:45,706 --> 00:11:49,107
the almonds are still encased in leathery hulls.   

227
00:11:49,109 --> 00:11:53,044
they flow through equipment that combs out debris.     

228
00:11:53,046 --> 00:11:57,115
the next machine, called a destoner, targets any rocks. 

229
00:11:57,117 --> 00:11:59,184
air blows through it to separate the lighter    

230
00:11:59,186 --> 00:12:02,054
almonds from the stones.    

231
00:12:02,056 --> 00:12:05,390
the almonds travel between a rubber roller and belt.   

232
00:12:05,392 --> 00:12:09,594
this spins off the hulls and releases the almonds.   

233
00:12:09,596 --> 00:12:14,532
the operator periodically examines the de-hulled almonds.

234
00:12:14,534 --> 00:12:19,538
vibrating decks with slots sort the almonds by size.   

235
00:12:19,540 --> 00:12:24,609
the system also shakes off   
hull material and vacuums it up.

236
00:12:24,611 --> 00:12:28,746
the almonds head to a gravity table for finer separation.  

237
00:12:28,748 --> 00:12:32,417
the spent hulls and other material float to one side   

238
00:12:32,419 --> 00:12:36,220
while heavier contaminants float to the other.      

239
00:12:36,222 --> 00:12:39,558
the in-shell almonds tumble down channels.     

240
00:12:39,560 --> 00:12:42,427
cameras examine the shells for imperfections       

241
00:12:42,429 --> 00:12:44,362
and look for contaminants,   

242
00:12:44,364 --> 00:12:48,566
then a blast of compressed air knocks them out of the flow.  

243
00:12:48,568 --> 00:12:49,968
these are some of the contaminants      

244
00:12:49,970 --> 00:12:52,904
that have been removed.    

245
00:12:52,906 --> 00:12:56,908
at another facility, machinery will now grade the almonds   

246
00:12:56,910 --> 00:13:01,112
according to the condition of their shells.        

247
00:13:01,114 --> 00:13:04,316
once again, the almonds fall through the open air,   

248
00:13:04,318 --> 00:13:07,719
and a computerized camera scans them for broken shells  

249
00:13:07,721 --> 00:13:09,387
and other flaws.        

250
00:13:09,389 --> 00:13:12,190
♪          

251
00:13:12,192 --> 00:13:15,059
a compressed air gun then knocks the flawed almonds 

252
00:13:15,061 --> 00:13:17,729
out of the mix.        

253
00:13:17,731 --> 00:13:21,132
the almonds bounce along a vibrating grid     

254
00:13:21,134 --> 00:13:26,204
and any kernels or missed shell fragments fall through. 

255
00:13:26,206 --> 00:13:28,607
finally, people sort through the almonds      

256
00:13:28,609 --> 00:13:32,276
and reject any that don't have perfect shells.   

257
00:13:32,278 --> 00:13:34,279
they also toss out any contaminants        

258
00:13:34,281 --> 00:13:38,015
the mechanized sorting system missed.     

259
00:13:38,017 --> 00:13:41,152
some buyers will pay a premium for the best nuts.  

260
00:13:41,154 --> 00:13:44,022
♪          

261
00:13:44,024 --> 00:13:47,526
the almonds with broken shells will have the shells removed. 

262
00:13:50,097 --> 00:13:54,099
these raw almonds are also sorted by size.    

263
00:13:54,101 --> 00:13:57,502
they flow onto a vibrating conveyor.     

264
00:13:57,504 --> 00:14:00,572
further along, the conveyor has holes.    

265
00:14:00,574 --> 00:14:04,776
the smaller almonds fall through
these holes and into bins.   

266
00:14:04,778 --> 00:14:07,379
the larger almonds continue forward.       

267
00:14:07,381 --> 00:14:09,581
these larger kernels are worth more         

268
00:14:09,583 --> 00:14:12,517
and will be sold separately from the smaller ones.     

269
00:14:12,519 --> 00:14:15,120
♪          

270
00:14:15,122 --> 00:14:20,125
as with the in-shell almonds, good looks are important.   

271
00:14:20,127 --> 00:14:23,294
a camera photographs the cascading almond kernels, 

272
00:14:23,296 --> 00:14:25,797
and a computer scans the images.

273
00:14:25,799 --> 00:14:28,266
the system knocks the less-than-perfect almonds 

274
00:14:28,268 --> 00:14:30,402
out of the production stream. 

275
00:14:30,404 --> 00:14:33,004
♪          

276
00:14:33,006 --> 00:14:36,340
next, the almonds head towards a robot.     

277
00:14:36,342 --> 00:14:38,876
along the way, another camera sends the images        

278
00:14:38,878 --> 00:14:41,613
to a computer scanner.     

279
00:14:41,615 --> 00:14:43,949
this one has been programmed to find chips,   

280
00:14:43,951 --> 00:14:49,087
scratches and even small broken bits.       

281
00:14:49,089 --> 00:14:50,688
the computer sends the coordinates        

282
00:14:50,690 --> 00:14:53,558
of the damaged almonds to the robot.         

283
00:14:53,560 --> 00:14:58,163
the robot then finds them and plucks them out of the mix.

284
00:14:58,165 --> 00:15:01,966
a human inspector now picks out any imperfect almonds

285
00:15:01,968 --> 00:15:05,103
that the robotic system missed.

286
00:15:05,105 --> 00:15:07,438
their flaws are just superficial.     

287
00:15:07,440 --> 00:15:09,040
they still taste the same,   

288
00:15:09,042 --> 00:15:12,244
so these almonds will be processed into chocolate bars, 

289
00:15:12,246 --> 00:15:17,181
almond butter or milk, baked goods and cereals.    

290
00:15:17,183 --> 00:15:20,218
the perfect almond kernels travel forward.        

291
00:15:21,989 --> 00:15:25,123
just ahead, machinery moves cardboard boxes     

292
00:15:25,125 --> 00:15:28,527
into an open position on a packaging carousel.    

293
00:15:28,529 --> 00:15:31,262
sprayers apply glue to the bottom flaps,      

294
00:15:31,264 --> 00:15:36,133
and pushers close them, sealing the boxes.       

295
00:15:36,135 --> 00:15:38,470
the almonds now arrive at a scale.          

296
00:15:38,472 --> 00:15:40,205
it releases them into the boxes

297
00:15:40,207 --> 00:15:43,007
in approximately 50-pound batches.       

298
00:15:43,009 --> 00:15:45,877
♪          

299
00:15:45,879 --> 00:15:49,281
these big boxes of almonds will
be shipped to other facilities 

300
00:15:49,283 --> 00:15:52,751
to be processed into other products.      

301
00:15:52,753 --> 00:15:56,087
smaller amounts will be packaged for consumer use.   

302
00:15:58,025 --> 00:16:01,760
a snack anyone can crack or enjoy pre-cracked,     

303
00:16:01,762 --> 00:16:04,896
almonds are a natural and nutritious choice.     

304
00:16:04,898 --> 00:16:08,500
no wonder they're consumed by the handful.        

305
00:16:08,502 --> 00:16:12,270
♪          

306
00:16:19,579 --> 00:16:24,049
♪          

307
00:16:24,051 --> 00:16:25,917
narrator: during the great depression,  

308
00:16:25,919 --> 00:16:29,120
motorcycles were an inexpensive
transportation option.     

309
00:16:29,122 --> 00:16:31,389
they were a cheaper way to get around town.      

310
00:16:31,391 --> 00:16:35,460
but these days, a motorcycle can be an expensive machine.  

311
00:16:35,462 --> 00:16:38,730
not for the penny-wise, high-end
motorcycles are engineered   

312
00:16:38,732 --> 00:16:42,734
and crafted for the rider with discriminating tastes.  

313
00:16:44,070 --> 00:16:45,870
♪          

314
00:16:45,872 --> 00:16:49,073
this is not a standard mass-produced motorcycle.   

315
00:16:49,075 --> 00:16:53,745
this performance cruiser takes 
things in a different direction.

316
00:16:53,747 --> 00:16:56,881
the high-end design is executed with precision,  

317
00:16:56,883 --> 00:17:01,419
with most parts machined specifically for this bike.  

318
00:17:01,421 --> 00:17:04,556
production starts with a conceptual layout.      

319
00:17:04,558 --> 00:17:07,825
the designer draws       
the motorcycle on a digital pad,

320
00:17:07,827 --> 00:17:11,162
producing a blueprint for the manufacturing process.   

321
00:17:11,164 --> 00:17:14,098
the manufacturer uses aircraft-grade aluminum    

322
00:17:14,100 --> 00:17:15,634
to make most of the parts.   

323
00:17:15,636 --> 00:17:18,436
computerized tools carve the solid aluminum       

324
00:17:18,438 --> 00:17:20,572
into the desired shape.    

325
00:17:20,574 --> 00:17:24,241
this part will be the motorcycle's belt drive cover. 

326
00:17:24,243 --> 00:17:27,445
the carved patterns make it more visually appealing,    

327
00:17:27,447 --> 00:17:31,916
and they reduce the cover's overall weight.  

328
00:17:31,918 --> 00:17:36,054
the company builds the exhaust system using stainless steel. 

329
00:17:36,056 --> 00:17:38,990
a technician welds the exhaust pipes together.  

330
00:17:38,992 --> 00:17:41,058
he then attaches several spring hangers     

331
00:17:41,060 --> 00:17:44,396
to the steel pipe assembly.  

332
00:17:44,398 --> 00:17:47,732
the next part is an ignition coil mount.    

333
00:17:47,734 --> 00:17:51,269
a ruby probe scans the part to find the center.      

334
00:17:51,271 --> 00:17:52,737
once it's been located,    

335
00:17:52,739 --> 00:17:55,072
a software-driven cutter descends,        

336
00:17:55,074 --> 00:17:57,609
and etches brand information and artwork          

337
00:17:57,611 --> 00:18:01,479
into the black anodized aluminum.       

338
00:18:01,481 --> 00:18:06,017
this steel structure will serve
as the motorcycle's skeleton. 

339
00:18:06,019 --> 00:18:08,686
the technician installs the 100-horsepower,      

340
00:18:08,688 --> 00:18:11,556
fuel-injected v-twin engine.  

341
00:18:11,558 --> 00:18:14,025
he then mounts the six-speed transmission system      

342
00:18:14,027 --> 00:18:15,560
to the engine.         

343
00:18:15,562 --> 00:18:17,562
it's equipped with a high torque shaft      

344
00:18:17,564 --> 00:18:22,833
that's shorter than usual   
to make the system more compact.

345
00:18:22,835 --> 00:18:26,104
he bolts it in place.     

346
00:18:26,106 --> 00:18:28,440
the steering stem has a framework at the base    

347
00:18:28,442 --> 00:18:32,510
with three openings known as the triple clamp.   

348
00:18:32,512 --> 00:18:35,647
he slides the stem into the tube on the frame   

349
00:18:35,649 --> 00:18:38,650
and screws a bearing onto the top.         

350
00:18:38,652 --> 00:18:40,118
he fastens it with a nut    

351
00:18:40,120 --> 00:18:44,122
that will keep the bearing pressurized.    

352
00:18:44,124 --> 00:18:45,923
he installs a second triple clamp     

353
00:18:45,925 --> 00:18:48,192
on the top of the assembly.  

354
00:18:48,194 --> 00:18:51,529
the center hole fits onto the nut.       

355
00:18:51,531 --> 00:18:53,898
he secures it with a steering head nut.      

356
00:18:57,004 --> 00:19:00,271
he inserts the suspension fork into the other two openings  

357
00:19:00,273 --> 00:19:04,175
in the triple clamps and makes some adjustments.  

358
00:19:06,546 --> 00:19:12,083
he places a carbon-fiber wheel between the fork tubes.    

359
00:19:12,085 --> 00:19:15,019
he installs the axle that links the suspension   

360
00:19:15,021 --> 00:19:16,688
to the front wheel hub     

361
00:19:16,690 --> 00:19:20,525
and tightens the titanium nuts on the axle for a better fit. 

362
00:19:20,527 --> 00:19:23,228
♪          

363
00:19:23,230 --> 00:19:25,830
next, he connects a six-piston brake system   

364
00:19:25,832 --> 00:19:27,365
to the suspension fork     

365
00:19:27,367 --> 00:19:30,168
and tightens the bolts that hold it in place.     

366
00:19:30,170 --> 00:19:33,838
this completes the front wheel assembly.   

367
00:19:33,840 --> 00:19:37,842
he now attaches the handlebars,
complete with dashboard gauges,

368
00:19:37,844 --> 00:19:41,513
controls and side-view mirrors.

369
00:19:41,515 --> 00:19:46,050
he makes the final connections for the electronics.      

370
00:19:46,052 --> 00:19:48,519
he encases the gauges and wiring with a part     

371
00:19:48,521 --> 00:19:51,523
called the front cowling.   

372
00:19:51,525 --> 00:19:53,791
the shape diverts air over the rider         

373
00:19:53,793 --> 00:19:57,061
and away from his or her face. 

374
00:19:57,063 --> 00:20:00,865
a two-piece gas tank will provide more capacity.  

375
00:20:00,867 --> 00:20:03,935
the tanks have been carved from a solid aluminum bar,   

376
00:20:03,937 --> 00:20:07,738
a process that's taken over 60 hours.      

377
00:20:07,740 --> 00:20:08,939
the tank on the right side   

378
00:20:08,941 --> 00:20:10,875
becomes part of the frame structure,    

379
00:20:10,877 --> 00:20:12,811
providing additional strength. 

380
00:20:12,813 --> 00:20:15,346
♪          

381
00:20:15,348 --> 00:20:19,150
he loops belt drive pulleys around shafts to transfer power

382
00:20:19,152 --> 00:20:23,020
from the transmission to the rear wheel.       

383
00:20:23,022 --> 00:20:25,490
the motorbike is now ready for the belt drive cover    

384
00:20:25,492 --> 00:20:27,625
we saw produced earlier.    

385
00:20:29,563 --> 00:20:31,429
while protecting the belt drive,

386
00:20:31,431 --> 00:20:34,666
this cover also gives the motorbike a distinctive look. 

387
00:20:36,903 --> 00:20:38,336
he mounts the left foot peg  

388
00:20:38,338 --> 00:20:41,406
to the frame through a hole in the pulley cover.      

389
00:20:44,244 --> 00:20:48,580
this high-end motorcycle is now
ready to hit the open road.  

390
00:20:48,582 --> 00:20:51,182
making it has taken 2 weeks.  

391
00:20:51,184 --> 00:20:53,251
preproduction fittings with the client        

392
00:20:53,253 --> 00:20:55,653
have dictated the position of the foot pedals,      

393
00:20:55,655 --> 00:20:57,856
handlebars, and the seat.   

394
00:20:57,858 --> 00:21:00,759
it's been tailor-made for a precision ride.     

395
00:21:03,063 --> 00:21:05,864
it costs more than many mid-range cars,        

396
00:21:05,866 --> 00:21:09,266
but this high-end bike isn't for the budget crowd.  

397
00:21:09,268 --> 00:21:12,603
it's for those who want a one-of-a-kind ride.     

398
00:21:12,605 --> 00:21:16,908
♪          

